    "<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nHis full name was Clyde Macaulay Davenport.  His father, Samuel <br />\nDavenport, was an avid reader of English literature, and named Clyde <br />\nafter the English essayist Thomas Macaulay (1800-1859).  Clyde, as his <br />\nchildren attested, was never quite certain of how to spell his middle <br />\nname.  He used McCalley, McCaulley, MacCaulley, etc. at different times.  <br />\nBorn in 1904, he did not have a birth certificate to consult.  When he <br />\nwent to apply for Social Security in 1966, he had to have a birth <br />\ncertificate created by affidavit, and he spelled his name Clyde McCaulley <br />\nDavenport.  The true spelling is verified in an old family bible owned by <br />\nhis mother, then passed down to his sister Nell Davenport Headrick, then <br />\nto her daughter Naomi Headrick Haynes, who had it in 2000.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
    "<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nWhen Clyde was born, his parents did not have a boy's name picked out and <br />\nagreed upon, so<br />\nthey told the doctor that they would decide on one and give it to him <br />\n(the doctor) the next time<br />\nthat they came into town.  They never did.  As a consequence, the birth <br />\ncertificate was filed with<br />\nno name.  They told Clyde that he was named after his father, and called <br />\nhim \"Junior.\"  However,<br />\nwhen Clyde started school, they had him to put his name as Clyde McCall <br />\nDavenport, Jr. (!)<br />\nThis was continued up until Clyde went to join the U. S. Air Force in <br />\n1959 and discovered that<br />\nhis birth certificate was blank in the name field.  Taking this <br />\nopportunity to dispense with \"Jr.\"<br />\nwhich was expected to be nothing but trouble in the military, Clyde <br />\namended the birth certificate<br />\nwith the name Clyde McCall Davenport.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
    "",
    "<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nDaniel and Mary Davenport were released by letter from Wolf Creek Baptist <br />\nChurch in August 1870.  They moved to near Pine Knot, McCreary County, <br />\nKentucky and formed the Bethel Baptist Church, which is still there in <br />\n1999.  Their daughter Elizabeth and her husband Jobe Perkins, were <br />\nalready living there when Daniel moved.  The church was formed in the <br />\nhome of Jobe Perkins.  Daniel's daughters Jane and Sarah, along with <br />\nSarah's husband Calvin Patrick, came by letter in 1887 from the Pleasant <br />\nHill Baptist Church.\n</p>\n<p>\nIt may be significant that Daniel Davenport and his son Andrew Davenport <br />\nmoved their families out of the Wolf Creek Community at about the same <br />\ntime in 1870.  There may have been some bad blood between them and the <br />\ncommunity, possibly involving ill feelings dating back to the Civil War.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
